[[File:Wall under Croagh Patrick.JPG|right|thumb|[[Croagh Patrick]] ''(pictured above)'', a holy mountain in [[County Mayo]], is climbed by thousands of pilgrims on Reek Sunday.]]
'''Reek Sunday''' (also Garland Sunday), is the annual national [[pilgrimage]] of [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]].<ref name="Pilgrims attend Croagh Patrick Mass"/><ref name="Dismal forecast heightens alert for Croagh Patrick pilgrims"/> On the last Sunday of the month of July,<ref name="Dismal forecast heightens alert for Croagh Patrick pilgrims"/><ref name="In the Footsteps of St Patrick">{{cite web|url=http://www.oecumene.radiovaticana.org/en1/Articolo.asp?c=305301|title=In the Footsteps of St Patrick|date=2009-07-26|accessdate=2009-07-26|publisher=[[Vatican Radio]]}}</ref> pilgrims climb Ireland's holiest mountain,<ref name="Pilgrims in Ireland seek signs of hope amid crisis"/> [[Croagh Patrick]] (''Cruach Ph<U+00E1>draig'') in [[County Mayo]], traditionally in their bare feet.<ref name="Pilgrims attend Croagh Patrick Mass"/><ref name="Pilgrims flock to Croagh Patrick"/> The pilgrimage has taken place annually for around 1,500 years.<ref name="Pilgrims attend Croagh Patrick Mass"/><ref name="Dismal forecast heightens alert for Croagh Patrick pilgrims"/><ref name="Pilgrims treated for hypothermia on Croagh Patrick"/> It is held in honour of [[Saint Patrick]] who, according to tradition, spent forty days fasting on the mountain in 441, following [[Jesus]] and [[Moses]].<ref name="Pilgrims treated for hypothermia">{{cite web|url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/ukpress/article/ALeqM5jok3zsjgMhjwN-gZYDbPAZH2AT2g|title=Pilgrims treated for hypothermia|date=2009-07-26|accessdate=2009-07-26|publisher=[[Press Association]]}}</ref><ref name="Pilgrims treated for hypothermia on Croagh Patrick"/> In reality, the modern pilgrimage is a long-[[Syncretism#Religious syncretism|Christianised]] variation of a ritual that dates back to pre-Christian, pagan Celtic Ireland, celebrating the Festival of [[Lughnasadh]]. Pilgrims come from as far as [[Australia]], [[Europe]] the [[United Kingdom]] and [[United States]] to complete the climb. Scientific analysis of the climbers first occurred in 2006 and Mass from the summit was broadcast worldwide via [[RT<U+00C9>]] for the first time in 2008.

Approximately 20,000&ndash;30,000 pilgrims participate on the day, compared to an annual climbing total of more than 100,000.<ref name="Dismal forecast heightens alert for Croagh Patrick pilgrims"/><ref name="Pilgrims in Ireland seek signs of hope amid crisis"/> The Archbishop of [[Tuam]] leads the climb each year. 150 personnel from eleven mountain rescue teams from across Ireland, including the local Mayo Mountain Rescue Team (MMRT) for whom it is the busiest day of the year,<ref name="20,000 to take part in annual Croagh Patrick pilgrimage">{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/breaking-news/national-news/20000-to-take-part-in-annual-croagh-patrick-pilgrimage-1841561.html|title=20,000 to take part in annual Croagh Patrick pilgrimage|date=2009-07-26|accessdate=2009-07-26|publisher=''[[Irish Independent]]''}}</ref> as well as the [[Sovereign Military Order of Malta]], [[Civil Defence Ireland]] and members of [[Garda S<U+00ED>och<U+00E1>na]] are involved in the climb.<ref name="Pilgrims to Croagh Patrick are urged to save their soles">{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/pilgrims-to-croagh-patrick-are-urged-to-save-their-soles-1835682.html|title=Pilgrims to Croagh Patrick are urged to save their soles|date=2009-07-23|accessdate=2009-07-26|publisher=''[[Irish Independent]]''}}</ref> Injuries ranging from cuts and broken bones to [[hypothermia]] and full [[cardiac arrest]] have occurred in the past.

== Recent years ==
25,000 pilgrims took part in the climb in 1999 in ideal conditions.<ref name="25,000 take part in Croagh Patrick pilgrimage"/> Archbishop [[Michael Neary]] of Tuam spoke on the mountain of the improving quality of life which Ireland was experiencing in the late 1990s.<ref name="25,000 take part in Croagh Patrick pilgrimage">{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/1999/0725/croagh.html|title=25,000 take part in Croagh Patrick pilgrimage|date=1999-07-25|accessdate=2009-07-26|publisher=[[Raidi<U+00F3> Teilif<U+00ED>s <U+00C9>ireann|RT<U+00C9>]]}}</ref>

Archbishop Michael Neary of Tuam spoke of the fear created by banking and commerce as well as by the Church and state at a meeting with pilgrims in [[Westport, County Mayo|Westport]] prior to the 2002 climb.<ref name="Archbishop says people feel let down"/> Pilgrims flocked from areas such as Australia, Europe, the United Kingdom and United States to climb Croagh Patrick in 2002.<ref name="Archbishop says people feel let down">{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2002/0728/croaghpatrick.html|title=Archbishop says people feel let down|date=2002-07-28|accessdate=2009-07-26|publisher=[[Raidi<U+00F3> Teilif<U+00ED>s <U+00C9>ireann|RT<U+00C9>]]}}</ref> Rain was said to have led to difficult climbing conditions.<ref name="Archbishop says people feel let down"/>

Around 20,000 people took part in 2006 during particularly bad weather of wind and rain.<ref name="Pilgrims flock to Croagh Patrick"/><ref name="Tough conditions for Croagh Patrick pilgrimage"/> Archbishops [[Se<U+00E1>n Brady]] and Michael Neary said Mass on top, with Neary appealing for kindness and goodwill to be shown to immigrant families.<ref name="Tough conditions for Croagh Patrick pilgrimage"/> Twenty-three people were airlifted or stretchered off Croagh Patrick with illnesses and injuries; two of these were hospitalised.<ref name="Tough conditions for Croagh Patrick pilgrimage"/> The 2006 climb saw the first scientific analysis of pilgrims.<ref name="Tough conditions for Croagh Patrick pilgrimage"/> 11,000 of them were surveyed with two thirds of the climbers found to be men, one third of the climbers found to be women, 5% of pilgrims coming from outside Ireland and 2% climbing in their bare feet.<ref name="Tough conditions for Croagh Patrick pilgrimage">{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2006/0730/croaghpatrick.html|title=Tough conditions for Croagh Patrick pilgrimage|date=2006-07-30|accessdate=2009-07-26|publisher=[[Raidi<U+00F3> Teilif<U+00ED>s <U+00C9>ireann|RT<U+00C9>]]}}</ref> 

Over 30,000 pilgrims climbed Croagh Patrick on Reek Sunday in 2007.<ref name="Pilgrims flock to Croagh Patrick"/> There were some minor foot injuries, whilst one man underwent a suspected cardiac arrest on the mountain.<ref name="Pilgrims flock to Croagh Patrick">{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2007/0729/croaghpatrick.html|title=Pilgrims flock to Croagh Patrick|date=2007-07-29|accessdate=2009-07-26|publisher=[[Raidi<U+00F3> Teilif<U+00ED>s <U+00C9>ireann|RT<U+00C9>]]}}</ref>

Over 25,000 pilgrims took part in 2008, the largest total in modern times.<ref name="Archbishop's appeal on Croagh Patrick"/> A live worldwide broadcast of Mass by [[RT<U+00C9>]] from the summit took place for the first time ever, with Archbishop Michael Neary of Tuam again the celebrant.<ref name="Archbishop's appeal on Croagh Patrick"/> Neary spoke of consumer values that he felt were seducing society.<ref name="Archbishop's appeal on Croagh Patrick"/> Over 20 priests were involved in the 2008 event.<ref name="Archbishop's appeal on Croagh Patrick"/> Injuries were very few.<ref name="Archbishop's appeal on Croagh Patrick">{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2008/0727/croaghpatrick.html|title=Archbishop's appeal on Croagh Patrick|date=2008-07-27|accessdate=2009-07-26|publisher=[[Raidi<U+00F3> Teilif<U+00ED>s <U+00C9>ireann|RT<U+00C9>]]}}</ref>

Only 18,000 pilgrims climbed the mountain in 2009;<ref name="Thousands attend annual Croagh Patrick pilgrimage"/> more than 20,000 had been expected beforehand and the 18,000 figure was down on the previous year.<ref name="Pilgrims attend Croagh Patrick Mass"/><ref name="Pilgrims to Croagh Patrick are urged to save their soles"/><ref name="Croagh Patrick climbers urged not to go barefoot on pilgrimage"/><ref name="20,000 to take part in annual Croagh Patrick pilgrimage"/><ref name="Pilgrims in Ireland seek signs of hope amid crisis"/> Weather conditions were particularly bad with many choosing to climb the mountain the previous day.<ref name="Thousands attend annual Croagh Patrick pilgrimage"/><ref name="Pilgrims treated for hypothermia on Croagh Patrick"/> Between five and six children contracted hypothermia on Croagh Patrick on Reek Sunday in 2009.<ref name="Dismal forecast heightens alert for Croagh Patrick pilgrims"/><ref name="Pilgrims attend Croagh Patrick Mass">{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2009/0726/reeksunday.html|title=Pilgrims attend Croagh Patrick Mass|date=2009-07-26|accessdate=2009-07-26|publisher=[[Raidi<U+00F3> Teilif<U+00ED>s <U+00C9>ireann|RT<U+00C9>]]}}</ref><ref name="Pilgrims treated for hypothermia on Croagh Patrick"/> Some participants sustained minor cuts, others complained of coronary issues, whilst one woman was airlifted off the mountain after breaking her ankle the day before and a man was airlifted to hospital after undergoing a suspected cardiac arrest on the mountain.<ref name="Pilgrims treated for hypothermia on Croagh Patrick">{{cite web|url=http://breakingnews.iol.ie/news/ireland/pilgrims-treated-for-hypothermia-on-croagh-patrick-420163.html|title=Pilgrims treated for hypothermia on Croagh Patrick|date=2009-07-26|accessdate=2009-07-26|publisher=[[Ireland On-Line]]}}</ref><ref name="Thousands attend annual Croagh Patrick pilgrimage">{{cite web|url=http://www.herald.ie/breaking-news/national-news/thousands-attend-annual-croagh-patrick-pilgrimage-1841958.html|title=Thousands attend annual Croagh Patrick pilgrimage|date=2009-07-26|accessdate=2009-07-26|publisher=''[[Evening Herald]]''}}</ref>  Prior to the climb, Mayo Mountain Rescue Team (MMRT) advised pilgrims to carry some sort of footwear but not [[flip-flops]], [[Sandal (footwear)|sandal]]s, [[stiletto]]s or [[Wellington boots|Wellington]]s; it was the first time they had ever issued such advice.<ref name="Pilgrims to Croagh Patrick are urged to save their soles"/><ref name="Dismal forecast heightens alert for Croagh Patrick pilgrims">{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2009/0725/1224251305099.html|title=Dismal forecast heightens alert for Croagh Patrick pilgrims|date=2009-07-25|accessdate=2009-07-26|publisher=''[[The Irish Times]]''|quote=THE WEATHER forecast for those hoping to climb Croagh Patrick tomorrow morning in the annual <U+201C>Reek Sunday<U+201D> pilgrimage could hardly be more dismal. [...] The pilgrimage has been taking place on the last Sunday of July for over 1,500 years. Usually between 20,000 and 30,000 people take part. Over 100,000 people climb Croagh Patrick annually.}}</ref><ref name="Croagh Patrick climbers urged not to go barefoot on pilgrimage"/> Pilgrims were also told to use a stick for walking, wear multiple layers of clothing and to scale the mountain at a slow pace.<ref name="Croagh Patrick climbers urged not to go barefoot on pilgrimage">{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2009/0723/1224251143218.html|title=Croagh Patrick climbers urged not to go barefoot on pilgrimage|date=2009-07-23|accessdate=2009-07-26|publisher=''[[The Irish Times]]''|quote=That is according to Mayo Mountain Rescue Team (MMRT), which has advised, for the first time, that people should wear footwear when climbing the 2,510ft (764m) mountain for the traditional <U+201C>Reek Sunday<U+201D> pilgrimage. [...] For those determined to shed their shoes, the rescue unit urges that they at least bring some form of footwear with them which they can put on if the effort becomes too painful or excessive. For safety reasons, the unit also urges that each pilgrim carry a stick and maintain a very slow and careful pace while ascending and descending the mountain. Flip-flops, Wellington boots, sandals and stilettos have been given the red card by the rescue unit, which also advised that climbers wear multiple-layer clothing which can be added or removed as required. [...] Upwards of 20,000 people are expected to climb Croagh Patrick for the national pilgrimage on Sunday <U+2013> among them the Archbishop of Tuam, Dr Michael Neary, who will celebrate 10.30am Mass in the mountaintop oratory.}}</ref><ref name="Croagh Patrick climbers warned of accidents">{{cite web|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/breaking-news/ireland/croagh-patrick-climbers-warned-of-accidents-14430806.html|title=Croagh Patrick climbers warned of accidents|date=2009-07-25|accessdate=2009-07-26|publisher=''[[The Belfast Telegraph]]''}}</ref> Archbishop Michael Neary said before the 2009 climb that people were <U+201C>searching desperately<U+201D> for hope in the <U+201C>menacing desert<U+201D> of [[2008<U+2013>2009 Irish financial crisis|the recession]].<ref name="Pilgrims in Ireland seek signs of hope amid crisis">{{cite web|url=http://www.thepeninsulaqatar.com/Display_news.asp?section=World_News&subsection=United+Kingdom+%26+Europe&month=July2009&file=World_News2009072631542.xml|title=Pilgrims in Ireland seek signs of hope amid crisis|date=2009-07-26|accessdate=2009-07-26|publisher=''[[The Peninsula (newspaper)|The Peninsula]]''}}</ref> In his homily on the mountain, Neary talked of the effects the recession had on family life.<ref name="Pilgrims attend Croagh Patrick Mass"/>

